rammer. You will be given a question (problem specification) and will generate a correct Python program that matches the specification and passes all tests.\n\n### Question:\nYou are given a binary string s and a positive integer k.\nReturn the length of the longest subsequence of s that makes up a binary number less than or equal to k.\nNote:\n\nThe subsequence can contain leading zeroes.\nThe empty string is considered to be equal to 0.\nA subsequence is a string that can be derived from another string by deleting some or no characters without changing the order of the remaining characters.\n\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: s = \"1001010\", k = 5\nOutput: 5\nExplanation: The longest subsequence of s that makes up a binary number less than or equal to 5 is \"00010\", as this number is equal to 2 in decimal.\nNote that \"00100\" and \"00101\" are also possible, which are equal to 4 and 5 in decimal, respectively.\nThe length of this subsequence is 5, so 5 is returned.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: s = \"00101001\", k = 1\nOutput: 6\nExplanation: \"000001\" is the longest subsequence of s that makes up a binary number less than or equal to 1, as this number is equal to 1 in decimal.\nThe length of this subsequence is 6, so 6 is returned.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= s.length <= 1000\ns[i] is either '0' or '1'.\n1 <= k <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def longestSubsequence(self, s: str, k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def longestSubsequence(self, s: str, k: int) -> int:\n        ans = v = 0\n        for c in s[::-1]:\n            if c == \"0\":\n                ans += 1\n            elif ans < 30 and (v | 1 << ans) <= k:\n                v |= 1 << ans\n                ans += 1\n        return ans\n```\n\nThis solution iterates over the binary string `s` from right to left. It counts all the '0's since they do not affect the value of the binary number and can always be included in the subsequence. For '1's, it checks if adding them to the current value `v` keeps the value less than or equal to `k`. If it does, it includes the '1' in the subsequence by updating `v` and increments the length of the subsequence `ans`. The check `ans < 30` ensures that we do not exceed the bit-width of typical integer representations in Python, although this is more of a safeguard given the constraints.", "estimated_date": 1655596800000}